post_text:
KGCS Families - A message from Dr. Benson, Superintendent. King George High School is aware that a student posted a message on social media last night claiming to be in close contact with a family member who suspects she may have the Coronavirus. We have investigated the claim in conjunction with the health department and the student's parent and have discovered the claim to be false.

We take the safety of our students seriously. As such, we did take immediate steps this morning to safeguard students including holding high school students in first period temporarily.

The coming weeks will undoubtedly involve all of us working together. We appreciate everyone's understanding and cooperation.

post_text:
KGHS Families - Teacher of the Year Nominations are here and due 2.14.2020.

Qualifications:
Individuals who possess a current renewable Virginia teaching license with an endorsement(s) in their assignment at KGHS are eligible.

Nominee can be a teacher, librarian, ITL, school counselor, or reading specialist. Teachers retiring from the profession at the end of the school year should not be nominated because the teacher must be active during the following school year.

Also, please consider whether or not the teacher you are nominating will be returning to KGHS in the fall.
http://bit.ly/37XTMs8

post_text:
KGCS Families,

Discover Your Future - Adult Volunteers Needed

This year KGCS is very excited to participate in the regional Discover Your Future event. We have partnered with the Fredericksburg Chamber of Commerce and surrounding school divisions.
This event is a career readiness exploration event for all 8th graders. Additionally, we have combined our annual WorkForce CONNECT event for 11th and 12th graders.

We are seeking adult volunteers to assist during the 2-day event that will take place October 9 and 10 at the Fredericksburg Expo Center. Additionally, there is a community job fair from 2 p.m. - 5 p.m. on October 9 that is open to the public.

Various volunteer opportunities are available. You may volunteer for a few hours or the entire day.

For more information about the event or to register to volunteer, please go to www.fredericksburgchamber.org/discoveryourfuture.

This is a great opportunity to support our students as they engage in hands on learning with our community businesses.

post_text:
Survey alert!
Each school year, the Virginia Department of Education (VDOE) is required to report to the U.S. Department of Education the “Percent of parents with a child receiving special education services who report that schools facilitated parent involvement as a means of improving services and results for children with disabilities.” To gather this year’s data, the School Year 2018-2019 Indicator 8 parent survey response collection period will continue through January 31, 2020.

Below is the link to the online survey for parents to complete in lieu of the printed survey. The online survey is now open for completion in English and Spanish versions at the following web links:

English Version: https://www.surveymonkey.com/r/VDOEEnglish

Spanish Version:
https://www.surveymonkey.com/r/VDOEEspanol

If you have questions or need assistance concerning the survey process, please contact Hank Millward, via telephone, at (804) 371-0525 or via email, at Hank.Millward@doe.virginia.gov.

Thanks to the generosity of the King George Education Foundation and our amazing staff, our students will enjoy innovative learning experiences. Congratulations to our inventive, imaginative, and superlative staff! The winning projects include:

-“Learning is Electric” by Yvonne Richard, King George Elementary School
-“Sealston STEM Club” by Sierra Hoskins & Theresa Lefeave, Sealston Elementary School
-“MakerSpace Tools” by Melissa Moody, Katherine Ross, and Ameer Mir, King George High School
-“Early College Career Exposure Program” by Jennifer Collins, Robin Mitchell, and Carleen Carey, Joint King George Middle School/King George High School

shared_text:
King George County Sheriff's Office
October 11, 2018 at 7:42 PM ·

Thanks to the Potomac Elementary School PTA, OmegaMan's superhero friend "Titan" visited the school to present a program aimed at discouraging bullying behaviors. "Titan" talked to the students about being a H.E.R.O. (Helping Everyone Respect Others) and being a "Dream Maker not a Dream Breaker."

post_text: Shirley Peyton left a legacy of love to her family, friends, colleagues and kindergarten students in King George County when she passed away just shy of reaching her long awaited retirement. The positive impact of her 45 year teaching career, her involvement with her church and leadership role with the local 4-H program, though, will long be remembered by generations of children through a camp scholarship fund created in her honor. The staff of King George Elementary created Shirley’s Child, a 4-H camp scholarship fund to honor her dream of academic achievement, emotional and social development for all children. Read more about Shirley's Child camp scholarship. ❤️https://drive.google.com/file/d/1YhTA21JUdvvGYuy_Lw16XJEc8eA6gc4D/view?usp=sharing

post_text: Superintendent Dr. Robert Benson was pleased to present a certificate of appreciation and commendation honoring devoted Ralph Bunche High School educator Mildred Ashton Holmes at the May 14 School Board meeting. Her exceptional communication skills and teaching proficiency, selfless contributions as well as her love for her students, inspired excellence for many years. Ms. Holmes graduated from Ralph Bunche High School in 1952 and went on to earn a BS and Master’s Degree in Business Administration. Phyllis Cook received the framed commendation on behalf of the Ralph Bunche Association. 🌟🌟🌟

post_text:
KGHS Athletic Director Alex Fisher and Girl’s Swim Coach Alexandra Bentz proudly celebrated the achievements of five phenomenal winter athletes at the May 14 School Board Meeting. The girl’s swim relay team (Emily Sizemore, Tamara Wheater, Emma Morrow and Caroline Bentz) were presented with rings for their victory as state champion runners up. Team member Caroline Bentz was recognized for being the state champion in 100 yard backstroke.
Ethan Indesth was also recognized as being a state runner up in the 2018 group 4 wrestling 3 day tournament.
Congratulations for your discipline, dedication and distinguished achievements! You make KGCS proud!

post_text:
Five KGCS staff were recipients of Charity Grants awarded by The Dahlgren Officers’ Spouses Club (DOSC) on May 5, 2018. DOSC operates “the Second Tour” thrift store on NSASP Dahlgren. Money received is given back to the local community and Naval Support Facility Dahlgren through charitable contributions. This year, 15 charity grants were awarded by the DOSC. Three students from King George High School also received scholarships through DOSC. 🌟🌟🌟
Read more about the grants awarded
https://drive.google.com/file/d/1otk54VUPdyNqtB6ms4yOdNDXom-pF3PZ/view?usp=sharing

post_text: You are in for a treat with the KGHS Theatre’s production of “Beauty and the Beast.” The beautiful sets and costumes are brought to life with the amazing talent of theater students, musicians, set crew, and sound crew, under the direction of the gifted director, Mrs. Katrina Wynes. Come hungry and enjoy concessions which help support scholarships for students. Purchase a Fan-O-Gram for the cast and crew to support the FoxSmart Center. You will smile as you enjoy the music, dance and story of love and acceptance in “Beauty and the Beast.” Show time is 7pm, May 2-5. Tickets are $10 (children 6 and under are free). 🌟🌟🌟
